review_blob:
Very nice and hoppy aroma with a bit of grain. Calendula and a hint of caramel.  
Dark Caramel-brown colour. Big white heavy head that lasts LONG.

Hoppy taste with really nice bitterness. Can taste a bit too sweet when temperated. Good citrus flavour and palate. 

Smooth and light, but still a holding aftertaste that fits the overall impression good.

One of the very best Norwegian pale ales. I prefer it served a bit colder than recommended temp .... about 10-12 celcius.

Not much aroma: Citrus, weak vanilla and apricot.

Smooth and refreshing taste with a touch of wheat. Citrus can be well recognized and associated with the aroma. 

Negligible alcohol feel wich neither is dominating in taste nevertheless of 5.8%

A good summer ale, but could be more powerful in flavour by my taste.

Can at home.

Light coloured, nothing to add to appearance for a lager being. (not more or less). Light foam that dissappear quickly. Good taste that quickly changes to a bitter aftertaste that carry the very revealing alcohol aroma/palate.

Can be a bit "tricky", because it doesnt give away its relativly high alcohol precent right away, so you might feel like downing it. But at a bit cooler than room temperature, it gives avay its real self; with LOTS of alcohol taste/aroma, and its NOT good.

Downing a couple of theese ice cold would definately get the party started. But I dont concider it a good beer at all.

After starting drinking real stouts, this one have really lost its charm.

Watery feel, A distinct coffe aroma. Big white head who stays hangs on the glass wall until youve drank up.

Can at home. Thin head that vanishes quickly. Yellow colour, not appealing.
Aroma: sweet, citrus, caramell. Watery feel. Mild citrus like taste. Best served ice cold. Typical boring norwegian "pilsner".
